Decision Tress
=================

#### _Donna Baret_

#### _March 29, 2019_

After running a GLM model in predicting a movie’s review, the Final Model for Predicting the Probability of having a ‘Recommended’ Review remark is : logit(Review = Recommended) = -2.519170e-01 + 1.229775e-08 Budget + -1.786033e+00 Sequel + 1.311648e-08 Gross - -4.696765e-04 Screens

In this paper, we present different methods to do create the “best model” to explain (and/or best predict) the probability of a movie having a “RECOMMENDED” review.

Loading Libraries and Packages
------------------------------

A. Decision Trees
-----------------

### 1\. (CART or RPART)

Find/recommend a pruned (recursive partitioning) classification tree. Experiment/investigate on different strategies for growing your tree, and on different strategies for tree-depths and/or pruning methods.

Using RPART, we used the variables that are fund significant in our Generalized Linear Model, Budget, Screens, and Sequel. We ran rpart using 3 methods

1.  USing an unpruned tree

2.Pruning the tree based on a optimal complexity parameter value.

3.  Setting a complexity parameter

We will compare the trees based on their relative error, xerror, and xstd. Moreover, we will also compare their prediction accuracies.

### 2.(CHAID)

Find/recommend a CHAID-based tree. Consider using either equal frequencies or equal widths to define 10 bins (or categories) for (each of the) continuous variables. Also, experiment/investigate on choice of the level of significance (consider 0.01, 0.05, 0.10, 0.15, 0.20, 0.30).

    mydata1$budget <- as.factor( cut(mydata1$budget,10, labels=F))
    #mydata1$budget <- factor(round(mydata1$budget))
    mydata1$screens <- as.factor( cut(mydata1$screens,10, labels=F))
    
    is.factor(mydata1$sequel)

    ## [1] TRUE

    cc1 <- chaid_control(alpha2 = 0.01)
    cc2 <- chaid_control(alpha2 = 0.05)
    cc3 <- chaid_control(alpha2 = 0.10)
    cc4 <- chaid_control(alpha2 = 0.15)
    cc5 <- chaid_control(alpha2 = 0.20)
    cc6 <- chaid_control(alpha2 = 0.30)

B. Non-Linear Classifiers
-------------------------

1.  (kNN or k nearest neighbors) Using insights from your decision trees and/or from your recommended GLM/logistic model (from Project 1), find/recommend a kNN-based classification model. Exclude SEQUEL as a predictor variable. Experiment on the choice of distance measure and the value of k (neighborhood size).

sing insights from your decision trees and/or from your recommended GLM/logistic model (from Project 1), we use budget sequence and sequel to classify if a movie will have a movie is recommended by majority of the critics or not. In this classification, we exclude sequel and experiment on the choice of distance measure (Euclidean , Squared Euclidean) and the value of recommended size ( k= 3, k=10)

3.  Non-Linear Classifiers- Budget, Screens

Linear model can take in any types of values and interpretation of results is intuitive except for the fact that interpretation is just linear. Classifying using Decision Trees such as RPART and CHAID is pretty straight forward too and requires little effort on interpretation, moreover, it does not require a linear relationships between the variables. However, CHAID requires a little more step in terms of data preparation as it does not accept continuous variables. Nevertheless, interpretation is straightforward too. Non- Linear classifiers – QDA and KNN led to good clasification results too. However, it doesn’t accept categorical independent variables which limited our variable classifiers.
